$$  I want to find the minimum of $f$ restricted to the level set $g(x,y)=k$. The function $f$ and $g$ are differentiable and $\nabla g(x,y)=(y,x)\neq0$ for every $(x,y) \in \mathbb R^2_{> 0}$, then I can apply lagrange multipliers to find the critical points of f restricted to that region. By the equation $\nabla f(x,y)=\lambda\nabla g(xy)$ I get that $(1,1)=\lambda (y,x)$, which means $x=y$. By the conditions of the problem, it is required that the points of the form $(x,x)$ live in the level set. So, the only critical point is $(\sqrt{k},\sqrt{k})$. 
My question is, how can I prove that at $(\sqrt{k},\sqrt{k})$, $f|_S$ attains a minimum?
